  "target_response": {
    "text": "On training: yes, with an easy day — and the 188 itself needs reframing rather than worry. Your max of 190 bpm is an age-based estimate, not a measured ceiling; true maxes routinely sit a few beats either side of the formula, and touching 188 bpm in the final reps of hard intervals can happen in normal hard training. A watch can't assess heart damage in either direction — that isn't a question this data can answer. For training readiness only, the morning inputs are not waving you off: recovery at 61%, HRV of 55 ms essentially at your 30-day baseline of 55.8 ms, and resting heart rate of 54 bpm near its 53.9 mean. Recommendation: easy aerobic today, roughly 40 min at conversational effort, because yesterday's session earns a light day regardless. Chest pain, dizziness, or fluttering during efforts is a doctor conversation, not a data one — and you've described none of those.",
